{"type":"message","id":"60f335a8","parentId":"b95f2b66","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:04:27.452Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Mon 2026-03-09 19:04 EST] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: # TASK: Validate Salesforce Architect ↔ Auditor Real Integration\n\n## CONTEXT\nThe integration between `salesforce-architect` and `salesforce-code-auditor` is documented but NOT VERIFIED with real data flow. There's no evidence that architect can actually call auditor and consume its outputs.\n\n## PROBLEM ANALYSIS\nCurrent state (unverified):\n- Integration documented in SKILL.md files\n- No evidence of real data flow between components\n- Unknown if architect can actually call auditor\n- Unknown if auditor outputs are consumable by architect\n- Unknown if project routing is preserved\n- Unknown if artifacts stay in project folder\n\nRequired state (verified):\n- Architect can call auditor with real project data\n- Auditor returns outputs architect can consume\n- Project routing preserved through integration\n- Artifacts stay in project folder\n- Architect can use audit findings in architectural reasoning\n\n## YOUR MISSION\nProve the REAL integration between salesforce-architect and salesforce-code-auditor.\n\n## SPECIFIC REQUIREMENTS\n\n### 1. Test Real Integration Flow\n- Create test project with real Salesforce requirements\n- Architect initiates audit via real integration (not simulated)\n- Auditor processes real code samples\n- Architect consumes audit findings\n- Verify complete data flow end-to-end\n\n### 2. Verify Integration Points\n- Architect → Auditor: Call with real project context\n- Auditor → Architect: Return consumable findings\n- Project context preserved through handoff\n- Artifact containment verified\n\n### 3. Test Integration in Real Scenarios\n- Use real project from architect pipeline\n- Trigger audit as part of architectural process\n- Verify findings influence architectural decisions\n- Ensure integration doesn't break existing functionality\n\n### 4. Validate Output Usability\n- Architect can parse and use audit findings\n- Findings integrated into architectural artifacts\n- Audit results influence DoD validation\n- Integration supports real decision-making\n\n## TEST APPROACH\n1. **Create Real Test Project**: Use architect to create project with audit requirement\n2. **Trigger Real Audit**: Architect calls auditor with real project data\n3. **Process Real Code**: Auditor analyzes real Salesforce samples\n4. **Consume Findings**: Architect uses findings in architectural process\n5. **Verify Integration**: Check data flow, artifact containment, routing\n\n## DELIVERABLES\n1. **Integration evidence** showing:\n   - Real architect → auditor call (not simulated)\n   - Real auditor → architect data flow\n   - Project context preserved\n   - Artifact containment verified\n2. **Usability evidence** showing:\n   - Architect can parse and use audit findings\n   - Findings influence architectural artifacts\n   - Integration supports real decision-making\n3. **Classification evidence**:\n   - INTEGRATION FUNCTIONAL: All tests pass, real data flow\n   - INTEGRATION PARTIAL: Some integration works but limitations\n   - INTEGRATION SIMULATED: No real data flow, only documentation\n\n## EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS (Anti-simulation)\n- NO simulated integration calls\n- NO placeholder data flow\n- REAL architect invoking real auditor\n- REAL data flowing between components\n- REAL artifact creation and consumption\n\n## TEST SCENARIOS\n1. **Basic Integration Test**: Architect calls auditor, gets findings\n2. **Project Context Test**: Project routing preserved through integration\n3. **Artifact Containment Test**: All artifacts stay in project folder\n4. **Decision Influence Test**: Audit findings influence architectural decisions\n\n## TIMELINE\n- Start: Immediate\n- Complete: Within 30 minutes\n- Report: Concise handoff with evidence\n\n## SUCCESS CRITERIA\nIntegration classification:\n- **FUNCTIONAL**: Real data flow, architect consumes findings, project routing preserved\n- **PARTIAL**: Some integration works but gaps exist\n- **SIMULATED**: No real data flow, integration exists only in documentation\n\nFocus on proving REAL integration, not documented integration."}],"timestamp":1773101067449}}
{"type":"message","id":"fe55f73a","parentId":"60f335a8","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:04:33.120Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I'll validate the real integration between Salesforce Architect and Salesforce Code Auditor. Let me start by examining the current state of both skills and their integration documentation."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_C19hS5MhLWlBpGbMogg5ShmP","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/salesforce-architect/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-chat","usage":{"input":12209,"output":91,"cacheRead":2304,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":14604,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773101067451}}
{"type":"message","id":"43646812","parentId":"fe55f73a","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:04:33.126Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_C19hS5MhLWlBpGbMogg5ShmP","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: salesforce-architect\ndescription: Production-ready skill for analyzing complex business processes, extracting requirements, producing Salesforce architecture decisions, generating FIT/GAP analysis, functional design documentation, data models, and validating architecture using official Salesforce documentation only.\nuser-invocable: true\ncommand-dispatch: salesforce-architect\n---\n\n# Salesforce Architect Skill\n\n## Overview\nA production‑ready skill for analyzing complex business processes, extracting requirements, producing Salesforce architecture decisions, generating FIT/GAP analysis, functional design documentation, data models, and validating architecture using official Salesforce documentation only.\n\n## CRITICAL RULE – USE WORKSPACE REFERENCES\nThe skill must read and consult the following reference PDFs (located in `<workspace>/references/`) before generating any output artifacts:\n\n1. `_F3.1 Definición de diseño funcional VF.pdf` – defines the structure of the Functional Design document.\n2. `IDEINCA - Matriz FIT and GAP.pdf` – defines the structure and fields of the FIT/GAP matrix.\n3. `IDEINCA - Documento Funcional V1NoGAPs.pdf` – example of a completed functional design.\n4. `Diseño Funcional(Modelo de datos) - IDEINCA.xlsx.pdf` – example data model structure.\n\nIf any of these documents are missing, the skill must:\n1. Stop execution\n2. Emit an incident\n3. Ask the user to confirm the references location\n\n## HARDENED GOVERNANCE REFERENCES (NEW)\nThe skill must also consult the following governance references (located in `skills/salesforce-architect/references/`):\n\n1. `SALESFORCE_ROLE_MODEL.md` – stable role definitions and boundaries\n2. `ROLE_ASSIGNMENT_RULES.md` – rules for assigning specialist roles\n3. `DEFINITION_OF_DONE_BY_ROLE.md` – completion criteria per role\n4. `SALESFORCE_PROJECT_STATE_MACHINE.md` – project lifecycle states\n5. `ARCHITECT_REVIEW_PROTOCOL.md` – standardized review process\n6. `CODE_AUDIT_HANDOFF_MODES.md` – architect ↔ auditor governance\n\nThese are **reference assets, not runtime-generated**. The architect must:\n- Select from pre-defined roles, not invent new ones\n- Apply DoD consistently across all specialist work\n- Enforce state machine transitions\n- Follow review protocol for all validations\n- Use appropriate handoff modes with code auditor\n\n## Salesforce Documentation Evidence Policy\nAllowed domains:\n- `help.salesforce.com`\n- `developer.salesforce.com`\n- `architect.salesforce.com`\n- `trailhead.salesforce.com`\n\nEvery architecture decision must include a reference link to official Salesforce documentation. If evidence cannot be found:\n- Mark the decision `UNVERIFIED`\n- Request clarification from the user\n- Do not finalize the design\n\n## Supported Clouds\n- Sales Cloud\n- Service Cloud\n- Field Service\n- Financial Services Cloud\n- Data Cloud\n- Agentforce\n- OmniStudio\n- Digital Engagement\n- Experience Cloud\n\nThe skill must evaluate licensing constraints before recommending features. For example: if Field Service licenses are unavailable, propose a custom visit management solution instead of FSL.\n\n## Skill Directory Structure\n```\nskills/salesforce-architect/\n├── SKILL.md (this file)\n├── scripts/\n│   ├── run_pipeline.py          # Main orchestrator\n│   ├── stage1_discovery.py\n│   ├── stage2_requirements.py\n│   ├── stage3_fit_gap.py\n│   ├── stage4_functional_design.py\n│   ├── stage5_data_model.py\n│   ├── stage6_arch_validation.py\n│   ├── stage7_export.py\n│   ├── official_docs_retrieval.py\n│   ├── debate_mode.py\n│   ├── learning_emit.py\n│   └── utils_io.py\n├── references/\n│   ├── TEMPLATES_INDEX.md\n│   ├── EC0249_mapping.md\n│   ├── VF_functional_design_mapping.md\n│   ├── FitGap_mapping.md\n│   ├── DataModel_mapping.md\n│   ├── Salesforce_official_whitelist.md\n│   └── pattern_keys.md\n└── examples/\n    ├── example_minimum_inputs.md\n    ├── example_with_transcript.md\n    ├── example_with_scope_fitgap.md\n    └── example_end_to_end.md\n```\n\n## Runtime Project Structure\nWhen executing the skill, a new project folder is created under `workspace/projects/<project_key>/` with the following layout:\n\n```\nworkspace/projects/<project_key>/\n├── discovery/\n│   ├── Discovery_Report.md\n│   ├── Discovery_Process_Analysis.md\n│   └── Discovery_QA.xlsx\n├── fit_gap/\n│   └── Fit_Gap_Matrix.xlsx\n├── design/\n│   └── Functional_Design.docx\n├── data_model/\n│   └── Data_Model.xlsx\n├── architecture/\n│   ├── Architecture_Overview.md\n│   └── Evidence_Log.md\n├── evidence/\n│   └── Evidence_Log.md (symlink or copy)\n└── README.md\n\n## HARDENED PROJECT ROUTING BEHAVIOR (RUNTIME ENFORCEMENT)\n\n### Project Owner Discipline\nThe architect acts as the **single governing skill** for all Salesforce work. Every execution must:\n\n1. **Identify project_key**: Extract or generate from request context\n2. **Check project existence**: Look for existing `workspace/projects/<project_key>/`\n3. **Create if missing**: Initialize with standard structure\n4. **Route all artifacts**: No Salesforce artifacts outside project folder\n5. **Classify request type**:\n   - New work (new project or phase)\n   - Artifact update (revision of existing)\n   - Review (architect validation)\n   - Correction (address issues)\n   - Code audit (technical validation)\n   - Remediation (fix audit findings)\n\n### Project README Governance\nThe architect must maintain and update `workspace/projects/<project_key>/README.md` with:\n\n```\n# Project: <project_key>\n\n## Current State: <state from state machine>\n- Entered: <timestamp>\n- Validated: <timestamp>\n\n## State History\n- DISCOVERY: <start> - <end>\n- REQUIREMENTS: <start> - <end>\n- FIT_GAP: <start> - <end>\n- DESIGN: <start> - <end>\n- DATA_MODEL: <start> - <end>\n- ARCH_REVIEW: <start> - <end>\n- CODE_AUDIT: <start> - <end>\n- REMEDIATION: <start> - <end>\n- FINALIZED: <start> - <end>\n\n## Artifact Versions\n- Discovery: v<version>\n- Requirements: v<version>\n- Fit/Gap: v<version>\n- Design: v<version>\n- Data Model: v<version>\n- Architecture Review: v<version>\n- Code Audit: v<version> (if exists)\n- Remediation: v<version> (if exists)\n\n## Code Audits\n- Case ID: <case_id>\n- Mode: <A/B/C>\n- Date: <timestamp>\n- Findings: <summary>\n- Status: <open/in remediation/closed>\n\n## Next Actions\n- [ ] Action 1\n- [ ] Action 2\n```\n\n### Artifact Containment Rule\n**NO Salesforce artifact may be created outside:**\n`<workspace>/projects/<project_key>/...`\n\n**Exceptions**: Only global references in `<workspace>/references/`\n\n**Violation response**: Emit incident `salesforce|PROJECT_ROUTING|artifact_outside_project|blocked`\n```\n\n## Pipeline Stages\n\n### Stage 0 – Intake Gate\n**Mandatory inputs** (block pipeline if missing):\n- Project name\n- Industry\n- Country\n- Salesforce clouds licensed\n- User count\n- Process description\n- Implementation scope\n\nIf any mandatory input is missing, generate discovery questions and stop.\n\n### Stage 1 – Discovery (EC0249)\nExtract actors, processes, events, systems, unknowns from transcripts/notes/SOW.\n**Outputs:**\n- `Discovery_Report.md`\n- `Discovery_Process_Analysis.md`\n- `Discovery_QA.xlsx`\n\n### Stage 2 – Requirements Consolidation\nTransform discovery into structured requirements with:\n- ID\n- Process\n- Actor\n- Description\n- Trigger\n- Acceptance criteria\n\nIntegrations must not be assumed.\n\n### Stage 3 – FIT / GAP Analysis\nFIT = requested + in project scope, GAP = requested + not in project scope.\nMust request SOW/proposal/scope before classification.\n**Output:** `Fit_Gap_Matrix.xlsx` with columns:\n- ReqID\n- Process\n- Requirement\n- Fit/GAP\n- Justification\n- Time impact\n- Cost impact\n- Implementation type\n- License dependency\n- Risk\n- Evidence link\n- Status\n\n### Stage 4 – Functional Design\nStructure MUST follow `<workspace>/references/_F3.1 Definición de diseño funcional VF.pdf`.\nGenerate `Functional_Design.docx` with sections:\n- Introduction\n- Scope\n- Business process algorithms\n- System interactions\n- Object model\n- Automations\n- Security\n- Reporting\n- Risks\n\nBefore finalizing architecture, enter **Debate Mode** presenting 2–3 architecture alternatives with pros/cons, licensing impact, documentation evidence.\n\n### Stage 5 – Data Model\nStructure must follow `<workspace>/references/Diseño Funcional(Modelo de datos) - IDEINCA.xlsx.pdf`.\nGenerate `Data_Model.xlsx` with tabs per object. Each object must include:\n- Fields, types, required flags\n- Relationships\n- Record types\n- Validations\n\n### Stage 6 – Architecture Validation\nValidate against licensing constraints, Salesforce limits, security best practices, scalability.\n**Outputs:**\n- `Architecture_Overview.md`\n- `Evidence_Log.md`\n\n### Stage 7 – Export\nUse `python-docx` for Word, `openpyxl` for Excel. Export all artifacts.\n\n## Learning System Integration\nIf blocking conditions occur, append incidents to `workspace/.learnings/ERRORS.md`.\nExample pattern keys:\n- `discovery|MISSING|nonnegotiable|scope|blocked`\n- `evidence|MISSING|salesforce_official|feature_unverified|blocked`\n- `fitgap|FAILURE|scope_missing|cannot_classify|blocked`\n- `licensing|CONFLICT|feature_requires_license|not_available|alternate_needed`\n\nThen trigger learning‑loop fallback.\n\n## HARDENED SUB‑AGENT SPECIALIST USAGE\n\n### Default Execution Model\n**Sub‑agents as default** for specialist work. The architect must:\n\n1. **Select from role model**: Choose pre‑defined role from `SALESFORCE_ROLE_MODEL.md`\n2. **Never reinvent roles**: Use stable role definitions, don't create new ones\n3. **Pass task‑specific context**: Provide only necessary context to specialist\n4. **Review critically**: Apply `ARCHITECT_REVIEW_PROTOCOL.md` to all outputs\n\n### Runtime Decision Logic\nFor each task, the architect must decide:\n\n1. **Single‑domain vs multi‑domain**: One specialist or multiple?\n2. **Specialist needed?**: Can architect handle or needs specialist?\n3. **Code auditor needed?**: When technical validation required\n4. **Output strength**: Is output strong enough or needs challenge?\n\n### Architect Roles Enforced\nThe architect must act explicitly as:\n- **Router**: Directs work to appropriate specialists\n- **Reviewer**: Validates against DoD and quality standards\n- **Challenger**: Questions assumptions, requests evidence\n- **Integrator**: Combines specialist outputs into coherent whole\n- **Project Owner**: Maintains project integrity and progress\n\n### Specialist Role Assignment\nAvailable specialist roles (from role model):\n1. Salesforce Administrator\n2. Salesforce Functional Consultant — Standard Clouds\n3. Salesforce Integration Developer\n4. Salesforce Custom UI Developer\n5. Salesforce Industries / OmniStudio Functional Consultant\n6. Salesforce OmniStudio Developer\n7. Salesforce Data Cloud Functional Consultant\n8. Salesforce Data Cloud Developer\n9. Salesforce Security / Platform Governance Reviewer\n\n**Assignment rules**: Follow `ROLE_ASSIGNMENT_RULES.md`\n\n### Output Rejection Protocol\nWhen specialist output is weak:\n1. **Specific feedback**: What exactly fails DoD or quality standards\n2. **Clear correction requirements**: What needs to be fixed\n3. **Priority classification**: Blocking vs. non‑blocking issues\n4. **Timeline for corrections**: Reasonable deadline\n5. **Re‑validation process**: How corrections will be reviewed\n\n**Incident for repeated rejections**: `salesforce|ARCH_REVIEW|subagent_output_incomplete|rejected`\n\n### Watchdog Registration\nAll long‑running sub‑agents must register with `agent‑watchdog`:\n- Expected runtime >5 minutes → mandatory registration\n- Monitor for stalls and timeouts\n- Automatic recovery escalation\n\n## HARDENED CODE AUDITOR INTEGRATION\n\n### Subordinate Validator Role\n`salesforce‑code‑auditor` operates as a **subordinate validator** under architect governance.\n\n### Project‑Scoped Audit Structure\nAll audits must be within:\n`<workspace>/projects/<project_key>/code_audit/<case_id>/...`\n\n### Architect‑Controlled Invocation with Project Control Integration\nThe architect invokes auditor using the integrated `auditor_integration.py` module which provides:\n\n1. **Automatic project control registration**: Every audit automatically registered in `project_control.py`\n2. **DoD validation**: Auditor outputs validated against specialized Definition of Done\n3. **Blocking logic**: Audit results can block state transitions based on severity\n4. **Incident generation**: Failed audits automatically generate incidents\n\n**Invocation Pattern**:\n```python\nfrom auditor_integration import invoke_auditor_with_control\n\nresult = invoke_auditor_with_control(\n    project_root=project_path,\n    mode='A',  # or 'B', 'C'\n    audit_objectives=['Assess code health', 'Identify constraints'],\n    scope={'included': ['apex_classes'], 'excluded': ['tests']},\n    context={'business_process': 'Order Management'}\n)\n```\n\n### Handoff Modes (from `CODE_AUDIT_HANDOFF_MODES.md`)\n1. **Mode A — Architecture → Code Audit**: Need technical truth before design\n2. **Mode B — Code Audit → Architecture**: Findings require architectural changes\n3. **Mode C — Design Validation**: Validate design feasibility\n\n### Enhanced Auditor Output Validation\nAuditor outputs are validated using `dod_auditor_validator.py` which checks:\n\n1. **Required fields**: Mode-specific required fields present\n2. **Evidence quality**: Code evidence with line numbers, context\n3. **Handoff completeness**: Structured for architect consumption\n4. **Mode-specific requirements**: Requirements specific to audit mode\n\n**Validation thresholds**:\n- ≥90%: PASS - Allows state transitions\n- 70-89%: PARTIAL - May block critical transitions\n- <70%: FAIL - Blocks all state transitions\n\n### State Machine Integration with Audit Blocking\nThe enhanced state machine (`state_machine_engine_enhanced.py`) includes:\n\n1. **Audit blocking checks**: Validates transitions considering audit results\n2. **Remediation paths**: Allows transitions to REMEDIATION for specific audits\n3. **Blocking summary**: Provides detailed audit blocking information\n\n**Blocking conditions**:\n- CRITICAL security vulnerabilities without mitigation\n- Audit outputs failing DoD validation (<70% compliance)\n- Multiple HIGH severity findings affecting core functionality\n\n### Required Auditor Outputs\nThe auditor must return architect‑consumable outputs:\n- Technical risks with severity levels\n- Security/governor findings\n- Object/field/automation usage analysis\n- Implementation constraints\n- Design alignment gaps\n- Remediation suggestions\n- Confidence levels for heuristic findings\n\n### Audit Integration with State Machine\n- **DISCOVERY phase**: Mode A audits to understand current state\n- **DESIGN phase**: Mode C audits to validate design feasibility\n- **ARCH_REVIEW phase**: Mode B audits for architectural validation\n- **CODE_AUDIT phase**: Formal audit as state progression\n- **REMEDIATION phase**: Follow‑up audits for fix validation\n\n### Automatic Incident Generation\nFailed audits automatically generate incidents in project control:\n\n1. **Validation failures**: `salesforce|CODE_AUDIT|validation_failed|dod_non_compliant`\n2. **Blocking findings**: `salesforce|CODE_AUDIT|blocking_findings|transition_blocked`\n3. **Handoff failures**: `salesforce|CODE_AUDIT|handoff_missing|contract_not_followed`\n\n### Project Control Integration\nEvery audit is automatically recorded in project control with:\n- Case ID, mode, timestamp\n- Findings summary\n- Validation status\n- Blocking status\n- Incident references\n\n**Example project control entry**:\n```yaml\ncode_audits:\n  - case_id: AUDIT_demo_20240309_143000\n    mode: A\n    date: 2026-03-09T14:30:00\n    findings_summary: \"3 critical security issues found\"\n    status: \"open\"\n    validation_status: \"PASS\"\n    blocks_transition: true\n    incident_id: \"incident_001\"\n```\n\n## PHASE‑AWARE RUNTIME BEHAVIOR\n\n### State Machine Enforcement\nAt runtime, the architect must:\n\n1. **Detect current phase**: Check project README and artifacts\n2. **Validate request for phase**: Is request valid for current state?\n3. **Determine artifact action**: Create new, update existing, or block?\n4. **Avoid regeneration**: Don't recreate artifacts unnecessarily\n5. **Version conservatively**: Increment versions only when substantive changes\n\n### State‑Specific Rules\n- **No FIT_GAP without scope/SOW**: Must have scope document\n- **No DESIGN without consolidated discovery**: Must understand what's being built\n- **No FINALIZED with critical audit findings**: All critical issues resolved\n- **No CODE_AUDIT without clear objectives**: Must know what to look for\n\n### Artifact Version Discipline\n**Naming examples**:\n- `Functional_Design_v1.docx`\n- `Functional_Design_v2.docx`\n- `Fit_Gap_Matrix_v1.xlsx`\n- `Code_Audit_Report_v1.md`\n- `Architecture_Overview_v2.md`\n\n**Version increment rules**:\n- Major changes → increment version\n- Minor corrections → same version with correction log\n- Format changes only → no version increment\n- Re‑creation with same content → no version increment\n\n## INCIDENT AND GOVERNANCE HARDENING\n\n### Governance Failure Incidents\n- `salesforce|PROJECT_ROUTING|missing_project_key|blocked`\n- `salesforce|ROLE_ASSIGNMENT|wrong_specialist_selected|rework_needed`\n- `salesforce|ARCH_REVIEW|subagent_output_incomplete|rejected`\n- `salesforce|CODE_AUDIT|design_alignment_gap|review_required`\n- `salesforce|STATE_MACHINE|missing_prerequisite|blocked`\n- `salesforce|STATE_MACHINE|invalid_transition|rejected`\n\n### Incident Reporting Path\nAll incidents use existing unified path to `workspace/.learnings/ERRORS.md`\n\n### Learning Integration\nIncidents trigger error‑learning‑loop for:\n- Pattern detection across projects\n- Guardrail promotion to AGENTS.md/TOOLS.md\n- Protocol refinement based on failures\n- Training need identification\n\n## Required Demo Execution\nTo validate the skill, run a demo project:\n```\nproject_key = demo_salesforce_architect\n```\n\nExpected behavior:\n1. Generate discovery outputs\n2. Block FIT/GAP if scope missing\n3. Emit learning incident\n4. Trigger learning loop fallback\n5. Generate Word and Excel artifacts\n\n## How to Use\n1. Ensure the reference PDFs are present in `<workspace>/references/`.\n2. Run the pipeline:\n   ```bash\n   cd /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/skills/salesforce-architect/scripts\n   python3 run_pipeline.py --project-key <key> --inputs <input_file.json>\n   ```\n3. For demo:\n   ```bash\n   python3 run_pipeline.py --project-key demo_salesforce_architect --demo\n   ```\n\n## Handoff Report Requirement\nEvery sub‑agent spawned by this skill must end its final response with a structured Handoff Report using this exact format:\n\n### Handoff Report\n- **Outcome**: success|partial|failure\n- **Incidents**:\n  - [TYPE=ERROR|NEAR_MISS|MISUNDERSTANDING|TOOL_FAILURE|MULTI_AGENT_HANDOFF; SEV=S1|S2|S3|S4] <brief symptom> (evidence: <1‑line concrete detail, no secrets>)\n  - Pattern hint: <optional>\n  - Prevention rule: <optional>\n- **Files touched**: <list or \"none\">\n- **Next action**: <1‑line suggestion>\n- **Watchdog fields** (required for monitoring):\n  - session_id: <your session identifier>\n  - run_id: <your run identifier>\n  - last_activity_at: <timestamp of last progress>\n  - progress_marker: <current step or checkpoint>\n\nIf no incidents occurred, write \"Incidents: none\"."}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773101073124}}
{"type":"message","id":"72b25d36","parentId":"43646812","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:04:37.552Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now let me examine the Salesforce Code Auditor skill to understand its integration capabilities:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_FFx8GMqfIzIndVrcSW4Pry7I","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/salesforce-code-auditor/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-chat","usage":{"input":4674,"output":77,"cacheRead":14592,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19343,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773101073126}}
{"type":"message","id":"192a4c14","parentId":"72b25d36","timestamp":"2026-03-10T00:04:37.567Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_FFx8GMqfIzIndVrcSW4Pry7I","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nname: salesforce-code-auditor\ndescription: A production‑ready skill for progressive technical analysis of Salesforce codebases (Apex, LWC, Visualforce, Triggers, Flows, Metadata) with token‑efficient auditing.\nuser-invocable: true\ncommand-dispatch: salesforce-code-auditor\n---\n\n# Salesforce Code Auditor Skill\n\n## Overview\nA production‑ready skill for **progressive technical analysis of Salesforce codebases** (Apex, LWC, Visualforce, Triggers, Flows, Metadata) with **token‑efficient auditing**. The agent requests only the minimal necessary code to reconstruct the real execution logic of a process.\n\nDesigned to **work together with the `salesforce‑architect` skill** as a **subordinate validator** under architect governance.\n\n## HARDENED ARCHITECT INTEGRATION\n\n### Governance Relationship\nThe code‑auditor operates as a **subordinate validator** to the salesforce‑architect. All audits must be:\n- Project‑scoped under architect control\n- Invoked through defined handoff modes\n- Returning architect‑consumable outputs\n- Subject to architect review and validation\n\n### Handoff Modes (Governance Contract)\nThe architect invokes the auditor using defined handoff modes from `CODE_AUDIT_HANDOFF_MODES.md`:\n\n1. **Mode A — Architecture → Code Audit**\n   - **When**: Architect needs current‑state technical truth before design decisions\n   - **Request**: Clear audit objectives, scope, context\n   - **Response**: Technical assessment, constraints, recommendations\n\n2. **Mode B — Code Audit → Architecture**\n   - **When**: Audit findings must change architecture decisions\n   - **Request**: Focus on specific concerns, architectural context\n   - **Response**: Critical findings, architectural impact, remediation options\n\n3. **Mode C — Design Validation Mode**\n   - **When**: Architect needs to validate if implementation supports proposed design\n   - **Request**: Design context, validation objectives, specific points\n   - **Response**: Feasibility assessment, gap analysis, implementation complexity\n\n### Required Output Format for Architect Consumption\nAll audit reports must be structured for direct architect consumption:\n\n```\n## Code Audit Report - Mode <A/B/C>\n\n**Project**: <project_key>\n**Audit Case ID**: <case_id>\n**Mode**: <A/B/C>\n\n### Executive Summary\n- Overall code health assessment\n- Key findings summary\n- Architectural implications\n\n### Technical Assessment\n- Code structure and organization\n- Design patterns used\n- Technical debt identified\n- Performance characteristics\n\n### Constraints & Limitations\n- Technical constraints for new development\n- Integration limitations\n- Scalability constraints\n- Security limitations\n\n### Risk Assessment\n- **CRITICAL (Sev1)**: Security vulnerabilities, data loss risks, performance failures\n- **HIGH (Sev2)**: Significant security/performance issues, major code quality problems\n- **MEDIUM (Sev3)**: Code quality issues, performance optimizations, minor security concerns\n- **LOW (Sev4)**: Code style issues, documentation improvements, test coverage\n\n### Recommendations for Architecture\n1. <recommendation 1>\n2. <recommendation 2>\n3. <recommendation 3>\n\n### Evidence\n- Code snippets supporting findings\n- Performance metrics\n- Security vulnerability details\n- Design pattern analysis\n```\n\n### Blocking Conditions for Architectural Finalization\nFindings that **block architectural finalization**:\n- CRITICAL security vulnerabilities without approved mitigation\n- Architectural flaws requiring design changes\n- Performance issues making solution unusable\n- Integration failures preventing core functionality\n\n**Incident emission for blocking findings**: `salesforce|CODE_AUDIT|design_alignment_gap|review_required`\n\n## Workspace Code Intake Model\nThe user must place code inside a case folder created by the skill.\n\nDirectory created automatically:\n`<workspace>/projects/<project_key>/code_audit/<case_id>/inputs/`\n\nSupported formats:\n- Apex `.cls`\n- Apex Triggers `.trigger`\n- LWC `.js`, `.html`, `.xml`\n- Visualforce `.page`\n- Metadata `.xml`\n- Flow metadata\n- DTO / integration classes\n\nThe skill **indexes files first instead of reading them immediately**.\n\n## Required Runtime Structure\n```\n<workspace>/projects/<project_key>/code_audit/<case_id>/\n  CASE.md\n  inputs/\n  work/\n  snippets/\n  temp_analysis/\n  outputs/\n  INDEX.md\n  MANIFEST.json\n  DEPENDENCY_GRAPH.json\n  ENTRYPOINTS.json\n  EXECUTION_TRACE.md\n  FINDINGS.md\n  TEST_MATRIX.md\n  AUDIT_REPORT.md\n```\n\n## Skill Directory Structure\n```\nskills/salesforce-code-auditor/\n  SKILL.md (this file)\n  scripts/\n    init_case.py\n    index_inputs.py\n    detect_entrypoints.py\n    build_dependency_graph.py\n    extract_snippets.py\n    generate_reports.py\n    utils_fs.py\n  references/\n    FILE_TYPES.md\n    REVIEW_CHECKLISTS.md\n    TOKEN_STRATEGY.md\n    REPORT_TEMPLATE.md\n  examples/\n    example_intake.md\n    example_manifest.md\n    example_audit_report.md\n```\n\n## PROJECT STATE MACHINE INTEGRATION\n\n### Audit Timing in Project Lifecycle\nAudits must align with project state from `SALESFORCE_PROJECT_STATE_MACHINE.md`:\n\n1. **DISCOVERY phase**: Mode A audits to understand current codebase\n2. **DESIGN phase**: Mode C audits to validate design feasibility\n3. **ARCH_REVIEW phase**: Mode B audits for architectural validation\n4. **CODE_AUDIT phase**: Formal audit as part of state progression\n5. **REMEDIATION phase**: Follow‑up audits to validate fixes\n\n### State Transition Impact\n- **CODE_AUDIT → ARCH_REVIEW**: Findings may require architectural changes\n- **ARCH_REVIEW → REMEDIATION**: Critical findings require remediation\n- **REMEDIATION → FINALIZED**: All blocking findings must be resolved\n- **Any state → CODE_AUDIT**: Can trigger audit at any phase if needed\n\n### Project README Integration\nThe auditor must update project README with audit information:\n\n```\n## Code Audits\n- Case ID: <case_id>\n- Mode: <A/B/C>\n- Date: <timestamp>\n- Findings: <summary>\n- Status: <open / in remediation / closed>\n\n## Audit History\n- <case_id_1>: <date> - <mode> - <status>\n- <case_id_2>: <date> - <mode> - <status>\n```\n\n## Analysis Methodology\nReconstruct system behavior in this order:\n\n1 — UI Layer\n  Identify entry points: Visualforce pages, Lightning Web Components, Aura Components, Flow Screens\n  Detect: buttons, actions, Apex calls, events\n\n2 — Controller Layer\n  Analyze controller classes called by the UI.\n  Detect: invoked methods, validations, business logic, SOQL queries, DML operations\n\n3 — Auxiliary Classes\n  Trace additional classes used by controllers: service classes, utility classes, validators, parsers\n\n4 — Integration and DTO Layer\n  Identify classes responsible for: callouts, response parsing, external API integrations, DTO transport objects\n\n5 — Triggers\n  Detect triggers related to objects used by the process.\n  Analyze: trigger context events, automation side effects, recursive logic risks\n\n6 — Metadata and Automation\n  Detect: flows, process builders, platform events, async logic\n\n## Token Optimization Strategy\n**Never load all code simultaneously.**\n\nProcedure:\n1. Index files using `index_inputs.py`\n2. Detect entrypoints\n3. Request specific files or snippets\n4. Extract only required methods using `extract_snippets.py`\n\nThe analysis proceeds **incrementally**.\n\n## SFDX Support\nSupports both:\n- Option A — SFDX structure: `force-app/main/default/`\n- Option B — loose files in `inputs/`\n\nThe indexing script must detect both.\n\n## Dependency Reconstruction\n`build_dependency_graph.py` must generate `DEPENDENCY_GRAPH.json` containing:\n- class dependencies\n- method calls\n- trigger relationships\n- integration flows\n\n## Execution Trace\nGenerate `EXECUTION_TRACE.md` describing runtime order:\nUI → Controller → Services → Integrations → Triggers\n\n## Audit Findings\n`FINDINGS.md` must identify:\n- governor limit risks\n- SOQL in loops\n- missing FLS checks\n- mixed responsibilities\n- weak error handling\n- security vulnerabilities\n\n## Testing Matrix\nGenerate `TEST_MATRIX.md` containing:\n- scenario\n- trigger action\n- expected system behavior\n- related code location\n\n## Final Audit Report\n`AUDIT_REPORT.md` must include:\n- Summary\n- Architecture Observations\n- Technical Risks\n- Performance Risks\n- Security Risks\n- Refactor Opportunities\n- Design Alignment\n\nThe last section must compare the real code behaviour against outputs produced by the **salesforce‑architect skill** when available.\n\n## Integration with Learning System\nIf critical issues are detected append incidents to `workspace/.learnings/ERRORS.md`.\n\nExample pattern keys:\n- `security|FLS_MISSING|apex`\n- `limits|SOQL_IN_LOOP|apex`\n- `architecture|MIXED_CONCERNS|controller`\n- `integration|UNHANDLED_CALLOUT_FAILURE`\n\nThen trigger error‑learning‑loop index rebuild fallback.\n\n## Demonstration Test\nRun a demo case: `demo_code_audit`\n\nThe test must:\n1. Create case folder\n2. Simulate input files\n3. Generate INDEX.md\n4. Build dependency graph\n5. Produce audit report\n\n## How to Use\n1. Ensure the skill directory is present.\n2. Run the pipeline:\n   ```bash\n   cd /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/skills/salesforce-code-auditor/scripts\n   python3 init_case.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   ```\n3. Place source files in the generated `inputs/` folder.\n4. Run the indexing:\n   ```bash\n   python3 index_inputs.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   ```\n5. Continue with detection, dependency graph, and reports.\n   ```bash\n   python3 detect_entrypoints.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   python3 build_dependency_graph.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   python3 generate_reports.py --project-key <key> --case-id <case>\n   ```\n6. For demo:\n   ```bash\n   python3 init_case.py --project-key demo --case-id demo_code_audit --demo\n   ```\n\n## Handoff Report Requirement\nEvery sub‑agent spawned by this skill must end its final response with a structured Handoff Report using this exact format:\n\n### Handoff Report\n- **Outcome**: success|partial|failure\n- **Incidents**:\n  - [TYPE=ERROR|NEAR_MISS|MISUNDERSTANDING|TOOL_FAILURE|MULTI_AGENT_HANDOFF; SEV=S1|S2|S3|S4] <brief symptom> (evidence: <1‑line concrete detail, no secrets>)\n  - Pattern hint: <optional>\n  - Prevention rule: <optional>\n- **Files touched**: <list or \"none\">\n- **Next action**: <1‑line suggestion>\n- **Watchdog fields** (required for monitoring):\n  - session_id: <your session identifier>\n  - run_id: <your run identifier>\n  - last_activity_at: <timestamp of last progress>\n  - progress_marker: <current step or checkpoint>\n\nIf no incidents occurred, write \"Incidents: none\"."}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1773101077561}}
